06542nam a22007815i 9780822375470DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20152015ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014042425  a97808223754707 a10.1515/97808223754702doi  a(DE-B1597)554418  a(OCoLC)1086416488  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aB4870.Z594bR474 2015 4aB4870.Z594bR474 2015 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a199/.497322300aRepeating Žižek /cAgon Hamza. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSIC00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Trouble with Žižek -- tPART I. PHILOSOPHY -- t1 "Freedom or System? Yes, Please!": How to Read Slavoj Žižek's Less Than Nothing- Hegel and the Shadow of Dialectical Materialism -- t2 How to Repeat Plato? For a Platonism of the Non-All -- t3 Materialism between Critique and Speculation -- t4 Žižek's Reading Machine -- t5 The Shift of the Gaze in Žižek's Philosophical Writing -- t6 The Two Cats: Žižek, Derrida, and Other Animals -- tPART II: PSYCHOANALYSIS -- t7 "Father, Don't You See I'm Burning?" Žižek, Psychoanalysis, and the Apocalypse -- tEnjoy Your Truth: Lacan as Vanishing Mediator between Badiou and Žižek -- t9 The Discourse of the Wild Analyst -- t10 "Vers un Signifiant Nouveau": Our Task after Lacan -- t11 Mourning or Melancholia? Collapse of Capitalism and Delusional Attachments -- tPART III. POLITICS -- t12 Žižek with Marx: Outside in the Critique of Political Economy -- t13 Žižek as a Reader of Marx, Marx as a Reader of Žižek -- t14 A Plea for Žižekian Politics -- tPART IV. RELIGION -- t15 The Problem of Christianity and Žižek's "Middle Period" -- t16 Islam: How Could It Have Emerged after Christianity? -- tAfterword. The Minimal Event: From Hystericization to Subjective Destitution -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRepeating Žižek offers a serious engagement with the ideas and propositions of philosopher Slavoj Žižek. Often subjecting Žižek's work to a Žižekian analysis, this volume's contributors consider the possibility (or impossibility) of formalizing Žižek's ideas into an identifiable philosophical system. They examine his interpretations of Hegel, Plato, and Lacan, outline his debates with Badiou, and evaluate the implications of his analysis of politics and capitalism upon Marxist thought. Other essays focus on Žižek's approach to Christianity and Islam, his "sloppy" method of reading texts, his relation to current developments in neurobiology, and his theorization of animals. The book ends with an afterword by Žižek in which he analyzes Shakespeare's and Beckett's plays in relation to the subject. The contributors do not reach a consensus on defining a Žižekian school of philosophy-perhaps his idiosyncratic and often heterogeneous ideas simply resist synthesis-but even in their repetition of Žižek, they create something new and vital.Contributors. Henrik Jøker Bjerre, Bruno Bosteels, Agon Hamza, Brian Benjamin Hansen, Adrian Johnston, Katja Kolšek, Adam Kotsko, Catherine Malabou, Benjamin Noys, Geoff Pfeifer, Frank Ruda, Oxana Timofeeva, Samo Tomšic, Gabriel Tupinambá, Fabio Vighi, Gavin Walker, Sead Zimeri, Slavoj Žižek   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aPhilosophy, ModernxHistory and criticismy21st century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aKotsko, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamza, Agon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoys, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g